    <div class="article story">
            <div class="articlePage">
                <!-- article start --><h3 class="byline">By Ben Levisohn</h3><p><strong>Valeant Pharmaceuticals International</strong> (<a href="http://quotes.barrons.com/VRX" target="_blank">VRX</a>) <a href="http://www.reuters.com/article/us-l-oreal-valeant-idUSKBN14U0O3" target="_blank">announced a series of divestitures yesterday</a> as it tackles its huge debt load, and the one thing that analysts appear to agree upon is that more will be on the way.</p>
<p>That was the <a href="http://blogs.barrons.com/stockstowatchtoday/2017/01/10/valeant-a-good-start/" target="_blank">view of analysts at TD Securities</a> <a href="http://blogs.barrons.com/stockstowatchtoday/2017/01/10/valeant-a-solid-price/" target="_blank">and BMO</a>, among others, who argued that Valeant will need more sales to meaningfully reduce its debt, and <strong>JPMorgan&#8217;s Chris Schott</strong> and team note that there&#8217;s still a &#8220;long road to recovery&#8221; ahead. They explain why:</p>
<blockquote><p>We continue to see a long road to recovery for Valeant. While select asset divestitures should help stabilize shares and address leverage concerns, we note that the $2.1bn of net proceeds from asset sales to date compare with a roughly $30bn debt position. Currently, we do not see a compelling SOTP argument for shares and see a number of uncertainties remaining around Valeant’s business. We remain Neutral.</p></blockquote>
<p>Shares of Valeant Pharmaceuticals International have dipped 0.1% to $16.39 at 10:13 a.m. today.</p>
